<p class="">    <h2>Key Challenges in the Modified Starch for Industrial Use Market</h2>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Raw Material Supply Chain Disruptions:</strong> The modified starch industry is heavily dependent on agricultural inputs. Fluctuations in the availability of corn, potatoes, and other starch sources due to climate change, trade tariffs, and natural disasters can hinder production capacities.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> Stricter regulations on food safety, labeling, and environmental sustainability pose significant challenges for manufacturers. Companies must invest in compliance-focused operations, which can increase production costs and limit market agility.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Technological Advancements:</strong> Rapid changes in processing technology necessitate continuous investment to stay competitive. Failing to adapt to advancements can result in obsolescence or difficulties in meeting customer needs.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Market Saturation:</strong> The modified starch market is becoming increasingly saturated, especially in developed regions. This saturation results in intense price competition, impacting profit margins for manufacturers.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Consumer Preferences:</strong> A rising consumer trend towards clean-label products and natural ingredients challenges manufacturers to modify their offerings. This shift requires innovation while keeping production costs in check.        </li>    </ul>    <h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Modified Starch for Industrial Use Market</h2>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Innovation in Product Development:</strong> There is a growing demand for modified starches with functional properties that enhance texture, stability, and taste in food products. Companies focusing on research and development can tap into this need and create specialized products.   